article.headline: Harvard 72, New Hampshire 67
article.story: ALLSTON, Mass. (AP) -- Evan Harris had 18 points, four rebounds and five steals to lead Harvard to a 72-67 win over New Hampshire on Wednesday. Drew Housman scored all 13 of his points in the second half for the Crimson, including two 3-pointers down the stretch. After missing his only shot attempt in the first half, Mike Christensen led New Hampshire in the second half with a team-high 18 points on 4-of-11 shooting. Tyrece Gibbs added 16 points and seven rebounds for the Wildcats. Down 70-67 with 12.9 seconds to play, Alvin Abreu missed a layup and Christensen couldn't convert a putback attempt for New Hampshire. Harris came down with the rebound and was fouled with 2.9 seconds to play. He made both free throws for the final margin. Abreu finished with 10 points, six rebounds and three assists. New Hampshire (3-2) led 22-21 in the first half when Harvard went on an 11-3 run, punctuated by a Harris steal and dunk with five minutes to play. Harvard's Dan McGeary hit 3-of-4 3-pointers in the first half, finishing with 11 points. The Crimson (3-4) led 37-33 at the half in a game that featured 15 lead changes. Gibbs paced the Wildcats (3-2) in the first half, scoring 12 points on 5-of-8 shooting.
